:: AffordableCSectionCrisis
<<set $step = 0>><<ShowInfo>><<set $day += 21>>

<h3>Emergency C-Section</h3>
<div class="consequence-text">
	<p>Three weeks into your doubled-up living arrangement, your wife goes into labor. Complications arise, and the doctors determine she needs an emergency C-section. The surgery goes well, and you have a healthy baby, but your wife's recovery will be more difficult than expected.</p>
	<p>You bring her and the newborn home to the crowded apartment. The other family has tried to give you space, but there's only so much space to give. Every cry from the baby echoes through the apartment. Your wife needs help recovering from major surgery while living alongside another family.</p>
	<p>The situation is becoming untenable.</p>
</div>
<hr>

<h4>How will you handle this situation?</h4>
<div class="housing-choice">
	<<link "Ask about bringing in your wife's friend for help">><<goto "AffordableInviteFriendChoice">><</link>>
	<p><em>Your wife's friend from the shelter has experience with C-section recovery. But the apartment is already crowded with two families. Do you bring her in despite the space issues?</em></p>
</div>
<hr>
<div class="housing-choice">
	<<link "Make adjustments yourselves">><<goto "AffordableWorkLessPayMore">><</link>>
	<p><em>Work less to help your wife personally, or offer to pay more of the rent in exchange for the other wife helping with recovery?</em></p>
</div>

:: AffordableInviteFriendChoice
<<set $step = 0>><<ShowInfo>>

<h3>Your Wife's Friend</h3>
<div class="consequence-text">
	<p>You ask the other family if your wife's friend can stay to help with recovery and the newborn. They hesitate. The apartment is already crowded, and another person would push everyone to the breaking point.</p>
	<p>"We need some time to think about it," they say. "It's a lot to process."</p>
	<p>But your wife's friend is ready to come now. She has experience with C-section recovery and knows how to help. Your wife is in pain and overwhelmed. Every day matters.</p>
</div>
<hr>

<h4>What do you do?</h4>
<div class="housing-choice">
	<<link "Bring the friend in anyway">><<goto "AffordableBringFriendIn">><</link>>
	<p><em>Your wife needs help immediately. You'll deal with the consequences later.</em></p>
</div>
<hr>
<div class="housing-choice">
	<<link "Wait for their answer">><<goto "AffordableRespectPrivacy">><</link>>
	<p><em>Respect the other family's need to decide. Find another way to manage for now.</em></p>
</div>

:: AffordableBringFriendIn
<<set $step = 0>><<ShowInfo>><<set $day += 14>>

<h3>Tension and Consequences</h3>
<div class="consequence-text">
	<p>You bring your wife's friend in to help. For the first few days, it's a relief. She knows what she's doing, and your wife is getting the care she needs.</p>
	<p>But the apartment was already too small for two families. With an additional person, it's unbearable. The single bathroom becomes a nightmare. Kitchen space is impossible to share. The baby's crying at all hours wears everyone down.</p>
	<p>Household responsibilities aren't shared evenly. Your wife's friend, focused entirely on helping with the baby, doesn't contribute to cleaning or cooking for everyone. The other family starts to feel taken advantage of.</p>
	<p>After two weeks, the other family has had enough.</p>
	<p>"We're leaving," they tell you. "We found our own place. We can't live like this anymore."</p>
	<p>Then comes the blow you didn't expect: "We're taking the car," they say firmly. "We put in half the money, and we need it. You made this decision without us - we're making our own decisions now."</p>
	<p>You try to negotiate, to offer to buy out their half, but the trust is broken. They take the car keys and leave.</p>
</div>
<hr>

