<h3>Personal Care</h3>
<div class="consequence-text">
	<p>You decide to take fewer jobs so you can be there for your wife during her recovery. It means less money, but this is what she needs.</p>
	<p>For the next three weeks, you're there. You wake up with the baby at night. You help your wife to the bathroom. You cook, clean, change diapers, and handle all the household tasks she can't manage while healing.</p>
	<p>It's exhausting. The other family watches but doesn't interfere - this is clearly your choice.</p>
	<p>But something remarkable happens. With proper rest and care, your wife recovers faster than expected. By the third week, she's on her feet and feeling strong.</p>
	<p>"I want to help," she tells you. "You've been doing everything. Let me work while you take care of the baby. We'll take turns."</p>
	<p>Together, you develop a system. She takes some of the jobs you would have turned down. You split childcare. The other family, seeing how well you've worked together, starts offering to watch the baby for an hour here and there so both of you can work.</p>
	<p>The apartment feels less tense. The shared sacrifice has brought everyone closer together.</p>
</div>
<hr>
<div class="success-box">
	<p style="color: green;"><strong>Success:</strong> By prioritizing your wife's recovery personally, you've strengthened your family and built deeper trust with the car-sharing family. The partnerships continue successfully.</p>
